Use your compressed air to blow out the inside of your machine. It is usually a good idea to start on the upper region of the computer, then work your way down. In this manner you can sweep out all the dust that settles on lower components in one run. Do not worry if you cause the blades of internal fans to spin. This is expected and it is important to keep these components clean. Be thorough, but do not press on cords or components. Also keep your air source a moderate distance from the component you're working on. Make sure to hold your can of compressed air upright. If inverted, it can be let out as a liquid which can cause severe damage to your computer. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/0/07/Clean-the-Inside-of-a-Computer-Step-7Bullet1.jpg/v4-460px-Clean-the-Inside-of-a-Computer-Step-7Bullet1.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/0/07/Clean-the-Inside-of-a-Computer-Step-7Bullet1.jpg/v4-760px-Clean-the-Inside-of-a-Computer-Step-7Bullet1.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":307,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":507.3626373626374,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

Compressed air is freezing cold when it leaves the can; don't let frost form on your chips. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/4/42/Clean-the-Inside-of-a-Computer-Step-7Bullet2.jpg/v4-460px-Clean-the-Inside-of-a-Computer-Step-7Bullet2.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/4/42/Clean-the-Inside-of-a-Computer-Step-7Bullet2.jpg/v4-760px-Clean-the-Inside-of-a-Computer-Step-7Bullet2.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":307,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":507.3626373626374,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

A lot of dust can be raised; try not to breathe it. If the PC is very dusty, take it out of doors before using the compressed air. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/0/03/Clean-the-Inside-of-a-Computer-Step-7Bullet3.jpg/v4-460px-Clean-the-Inside-of-a-Computer-Step-7Bullet3.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/0/03/Clean-the-Inside-of-a-Computer-Step-7Bullet3.jpg/v4-760px-Clean-the-Inside-of-a-Computer-Step-7Bullet3.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":307,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":507.3626373626374,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
